# Rename to CODEOWNERS and replace the placeholder.
#
# ENFORCED once the main-review ruleset is installed: a PR into main needs an
# approving review from an owner listed here — an approval from any other
# collaborator does not satisfy the gate.
#
# PHILOSOPHY (learned on the TaskFlow pilot): list EXACTLY ONE owner — the
# senior engineer — per path. Every other write-access collaborator is a
# junior contributing agent-assisted PRs, and the point of this file is that a
# junior's approval cannot clear another junior's PR. Adding a second owner to
# "unblock" self-approval hands that person the power to approve every other
# junior's work, dissolving the gate for everyone at once.
#
# The self-approval deadlock is real — GitHub forbids approving your own PR,
# so the senior's own PRs will always read BLOCKED/REVIEW_REQUIRED. That is
# expected, not a misconfiguration. Their merge path (and only theirs):
#     gh pr checks <PR>                    # must be green — this is unbypassable
#     gh pr merge <PR> --admin --squash    # waives ONLY the review rule
# The main-integrity ruleset has no bypass actors, so --admin still cannot
# merge red CI. (If your org has TWO true seniors, two owners is fine — the
# rule is "owners = seniors", not "owners = 1".)
#
# The last matching line wins. Route sensitive paths explicitly even though *
# already covers them — explicit entries survive future * changes.

*                              @YOUR-SENIOR
/.github/                      @YOUR-SENIOR
/CLAUDE.md                     @YOUR-SENIOR
/.claude/                      @YOUR-SENIOR
/docs/style.md                 @YOUR-SENIOR
# Stack-specific sensitive paths — schema, lint/test configs (coverage
# excludes are a suppression vector), infra:
# /backend/prisma/schema.prisma  @YOUR-SENIOR
# /**/eslint.config.js           @YOUR-SENIOR
# /**/vitest.config.*            @YOUR-SENIOR
